executive_summary_comment: The NSpOC is actively monitoring a non-UK fragmentation event involving ISS (ZARYA) (NORAD 25544) 1998-067A. Initial analysis with the limited data received so far shows the most likely time of this event was around 00:00 UTC on 01 January 2024.  ISS (ZARYA) is a 450000.0 kg civil spaceship satellite. Current tracking shows 18 pieces of debris in orbits close to the original object, though work continues to identify and catalogue other potential debris objects. This number could therefore change significantly as more data is received. Based on the limited information we have so far, our models show a most likely worst-case scenario of around 645 pieces of debris. This is a low risk event due to the number of fragments produced, with some UK licensed satellites, as well as Human Spaceflight Missions, seeing an increased risk of potential collision.
object_history_comment: Outside of the direct risk based on the fragments generated, there is potential longer term risk to objects on orbit due to other RSOs with similar bus or components thought to be related to the cause of this fragmentation.  There is likely 1 satellite on orbit that shares a bus type.
spaceflight_risk_comment: Due to the high mass and energy of this event, a substantial number of fragments have been generated. Work is ongoing to assess the risk to UK licensed satellites however it's likely that those at lower altitudes such as newly launched OneWeb satellites, Davinci and the Diamond series of CubeSats will have a significant increase in the number of potential collisions due to tracked and untracked debris. Both the International Space Station and the Tiangong Space Station orbit within the affected region and so we would expect to see a significant increase in risk over the short-medium term because of this event.
uk_response_comment: UKSA is the HMG lead for fragmentation reporting. Military sensors have been tasked to assist in observing this event. They will provide data that will enable us to better understand the number and distribution of the fragments. This is crucial for us to be able to quantify the risk to UK, Human Spaceflight and CNI assets. We will continue to provide updates on this event when possible however this timeframe can vary.
press_attention_comment: There is no media interest concerning this event. We do not indend to undertake comms activity in relation to the event at this stage.
